A quarter of a year ago, the Road and Motorway Directorate admitted: at the main road from České Budějovice to Lipno, an advertising billboard stands on our property by the state road.
But even three months were not enough for the officials to get rid of an unauthorized portable structure with a giant advertising poster.
As if no one cared that he was standing next to the road, in a fifty-meter protection zone, where for safety nothing is allowed.
Road administrators say they can't simply cope with the billboard because of the leaky law.
Maybe load it up and take him away.
"We must not just afford this," says Nina Ledvinová, spokesperson for the Road and Motorway Directorate, referring to the complex bureaucratic wheel, which must be preceded by the removal of the billboard according to the law.
The case of this particular billboard, the fate of which the online daily Aktuálně.cz began to monitor in detail in the spring, is not unique and points to a general problem that the state and authorities cannot solve effectively and quickly.
In South Bohemia alone, the editorial board counted dozens of similar mobile ads placed against the rules just next to the road or near the road.
The same is true of other countries.
"We have trouble forcing companies to remove the banners," confirms Jiří Klása, the head of the transport department of the České Budějovice Regional Authority, whose colleagues are dealing with similar stories.
According to Klása, the winding law is to blame for tying officials.
First, he must be intricately addressing the owner of the billboard to give the ad away.
But bosses of companies are often unrivalled or know the trick that Aktuálně.cz has already described in the past when it became more interested in the issue: just move the mobile stand with advertising by a few meters, and officials can throw the previous call to remove black advertising in the trash.
That's because the office has to determine exactly where the illegal billboard stands.
"If someone moves it and the coordinates suddenly disagree, it is viewed as a new device and we have to contact the owner again," explains Jiří Klása.
The new law won't help.
The change could be brought by a new law, which will ban billboards by highways from September next year and limit them even on Class I roads.
Critics point out that the rules for combating illegal and easily transferable ads will remain the same as before.
And the authorities won't be relieved.
Companies can still earn tens to hundreds of millions of crowns a year on the lease of illegal areas and no one can afford them.
For example, a billboard attracting Lipno belongs to the company Commerz Billboard.
Officials know her well: the České Budějovice municipality currently conducts three administrative proceedings with it for black-built billboards.
The company faces a fine of three hundred and thousand in every proceedings.
These are more advertisements that were placed without permission in the protection zone of the 1st class road.
The proceedings have not yet been completed, says Jaroslav Mráz, head of the Transport Department of the České Budějovice Municipality.
Advertising that Aktuálně.cz is not yet involved in these cases, but will soon be added to them.
According to RMD spokeswoman Nina Ledvinová, the company did not respond to repeated written requests for removal, and the case will be put on the table of regional and then probably magistrates.
Commerz Billboard is one of those suspicious companies that fails to contact.
She does not take over the post office and canceled the official seat in Žižkov more than six years ago.
It is unclear who is behind it.
In the past, the company's post office went to the South Bohemian entrepreneur Anton Fischer, who was famous for a sharp dispute with the head of the Czech representation of the Hyundai brand.
However, Fischer, whose Euro Billboard is renting and offering them to advertisers, has rejected any connection in the past.
This spring, when the RMD became interested in advertising at the Lipno initiative, Fischer had the state officials sent a letter to the mysterious company Commerz Billboard to his guesthouse, where the company is allegedly newly based.
However, even from this address, no one has called the highway administrators to this day.
Futile struggle.
Similar silence or opaque changes in settlements are not uncommon.
We gradually fined one company for two million crowns a few years ago.
But she changed the name and ID and there was nothing to deal with.
The executor returned the case, the ads continued, perhaps in other places.
We are quite helpless against such companies and their business practices.
It is like fighting windmills, one of the officials admits, on condition of the preservation of anonymity.
No one is yet addressing the amendment to the law in this regard.
Aktuálně.cz spoke to several MPs who were interested in the problem.
They have not yet developed any activity.
On the contrary, there were MPs who wanted to extend the deadline for maintaining billboards in the main Czech roads.
The government has denied this.
Billboards are not only a very sensitive and somewhat schizophrenic topic for national, but also regional and municipal politicians.
On the one hand, they know about the social demand for their limitations, on the other hand, they themselves need them because of advertising in election campaigns.
I do not give the rather established impression that when something does not work, it is necessary to change the laws.
