Russia and Turkey: An alliance of “incompatible”?
It was a gesture that ended in a crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and announce a formal end to the eight-month long verbal war and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterparty in the sumptuous hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted more to this reconciliation.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin was not smiling, and he was barely radiating warmth, even according to his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken of his “expensive friend” to Mr Putin – five times, as one of the reports reports.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia will not only return to their level before the crisis, but would be even better.
The next day, some of the local newspapers wrote that Erdogan acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm betrayed the exact opposite.
But the lingering cold that radiated from Putin showed that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: the shooting down of a Russian fighter jet by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow's reaction was furious at the time.
Putin handed out wounds around him and accused Ankara of slamping a knife in the back.
The scandal was all the greater because it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuild real trust will be difficult, perhaps even impossible.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
For months, state-controlled media has been campaigning a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara.
Suddenly it looked as if the Turks were to blame for everything.
More serious was accusations from top state officials that Erdogan's own family benefited from illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He strongly denied this.
But in St. Petersburg came an official message that it is time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin received an apology from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared a victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of the ceasefire's declaration are clear.
In the first place, Erdogan was almost deprived of power during a failed coup last month and therefore needs all his friends.
Repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey have also visibly shaken it.
There is also an economic motive.
Russian sanctions have had a severe impact - mainly the abolition of charter flights, which annually transport several million Russian tourists to the coast of Turkey.
This number has fallen by almost 90%.
As for Russia, tour operators and charter companies will certainly relax here when the flights are restored.
They make money from Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as the report in the newspapers Vedomosti said.
But the visit had another political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West as what he sees as a poor response to the coup attempt.
In addition, long-lasting hostile streak of talks on joining the EU and Putin's accession - who is eager to take advantage of the cooling and tear Turkey's ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly won bonus points when Ankara asked him for help from the elected authorities after attempting a coup.
You have to understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-rooted fear of regime change, it is a given.
So the summit in this pompous, seafront palace allowed Russia and Turkey to show what one of the analysts described to me as the “incompatible alliance”: how the forces of two countries that feel rejected and exploited by the West are joining forces.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly shown mutual reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently took the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey stand on opposite sides.
You could say that after nearly three hours of introductory talks, the two presidents said at a press conference that they had not even mentioned this issue.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answers to a question about the differences between them, while Putin decided to highlight these differences.
There is no clear agreement on the basis of which the two states could find common ground on the issue of Syria.
But after months of open hostility - and given the risk of utter catastrophe, when a NATO member of Turkey shot down a Russian warplane - it is certainly better that the two leaders at least speak together again.
