A court in France has rejected the orders of authorities in Calais to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the Jungle camp where thousands of refugees live.
During a court hearing this week, authorities in Calais argued that the state should be able to cancel a total of 72 makeshift shops where people sell goods inside the camp, from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, in makeshift restaurants they sell tea for 50 cents or basic dishes for several euros.
The Prefect Office in Calais argued that places need to be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes, and because they pose a risk of fire and health risks.
Humanitarian organizations said in court that shops and restaurants are vital and that free meals, which offers state-supported associations and other groups, do not provide an addition to food for growing numbers of refugees in the camp.
Disputed makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to people in need.
A court in Lille ruled that there was no legal basis to prevent people from running 72 makeshift shops, but said the Calais prefect's objections were "completely understandable."
Judge Jean-François Molla said grocery stores, cafes and restaurants have a much greater role than just serving food to people who "live in extremely desperate conditions."
He said the premises provide peaceful places to meet refugees and volunteers.
One of the places threatened with demolition was a cafe in the camp, the Jungle Book Kids, which is run by a non-profit organization and which offers 200 meals, English and French lessons every day, and asylum counseling for hundreds of unaccompanied minors in the camp.
