Luxury apartment in a new building in Vinohrady has a swimming pool and a whirlpool on the terrace.
Why did you choose an apartment in a new building?
We were looking for a carefree apartment where most of the care of the property is provided by the administrator.
The condition was enough parking spaces and an elevator in the house, which basically disqualified the older buildings.
Not to mention the problematic acoustics in old houses, problems with rocking the floor, high energy intensity and the like.
The condition was also large terraces, which the old development is not able to offer.
Other interesting visits can be found in the magazine Modern Apartment.
The entire interior was designed for you by architect Lenka Langerová with her colleague Kamila Poláková from the Artiga studio.
Why did you reach out to them?
Would you recommend working with an expert to everyone?
Cooperation with the architect would be recommended to everyone, if he designs an apartment from the beginning, because it is a very complex technical process.
The second plane is the design of the interior itself: designers have a significantly better idea of the range of possible materials, and based on the client’s wishes, they are able to match the interior appropriately.
We cooperated with the architect Lenka Langerová already on our mountain apartment, then on the basis of the personal recommendation of another client, and since everything worked well, it was a clear choice for us even when reconstructing our new apartment in Vinohrady.
What were your practical and aesthetic requirements?
We wanted a generous social-residential space with adequate facilities for a family of four conceived as a modern, but not cool interior.
The priority was to achieve the connection of the apartment with the terraces and to realize intelligent home control.
And, of course, it was necessary to ensure the quality of the execution.
Did you leave everything to the experts, or did you interfere with the final form of the interior?
We approved all designs, including technical drawings and samples of materials, but the design always came from the architects.
At the beginning, we set what we expect from the design, and showed some interior elements that we would like to incorporate into the design, such as carpets or paintings.
I think that our collection of mostly Czech authors, including the works of Karel Malich, Karel Vyschal, Václav Špála or Otto Gutfreund, the architect helped to orientate himself in our taste.
Also, the combination of black, white and walnut wood was the idea of the architect as well as individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. We then verified whether everything is tuning together with the help of visualizations.
Have there been any complications in the implementation of which you had to give up the original ideas, or vice versa, to accept new ones?
Perhaps only in the initial phase of the project, when we came to the construction at the moment when it was first possible to climb to the height of our floor, and found that the views we had planned would actually be shielding the surrounding buildings.
At that time, we literally changed the layout overnight from the ground up.
On the kitchen counter and for the lining of the fireplace wall, granite was used.
In the interior, wooden surfaces complemented by leather, for example, for the upholstery of the Dining and bar chairs Norma from Arper, prevail.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you going to make any changes or is there anything you wish you had differently today?
I believe that it is a modern air interior, which primarily fulfills its purpose.
We are not going to make changes, most of the modifications after moving in took place in the plane of the shielding and settling of the terraces.
Perhaps the only rebuke is to the floor, when walnut wood turns out to be too delicate for the household with a dog.
The Word of the Architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerová and MgA. Kamila Hornychová, author of the realization.
The apartment is on the top floor of a new building, so it was possible to make a completely new layout solution and several other modifications.
For the interior, an important element is the placement of sun tunnels in the ceiling of the hallway and the main toilet.
This gives us daylight to the darker areas of the apartment.
Also, direct access from the main bathroom to the roof terrace to the pool from USSPA is one of the construction modifications that was very beneficial for the function of the entire apartment.
There is also a swimming pool and a hot tub.
Compared to the French, you are not negative, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You come from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are originally from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, near the Spanish border.
I moved quite a bit.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
In France, I studied journalism, which made me get to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was starting to feel like I was choking in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere among people.
I thought every Frenchman was very negative.
People in France are negatively attuned in general, but lately it has gotten even worse.
Interestingly, you mention negativism.
This is how some people value the Czech character.
Believe me, you are not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not find it that way when they come to France, because they don’t see it as much as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
A big topic is money.
People feel that they have little money, while the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which I think is enough.
There is also a problem with people’s behavior towards Muslims.
That's completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street I was living in, my non-Muslim neighbor started looking at me through my fingers just because I was a Muslim.
It's like I'm some kind of evil.
That's why I didn't feel comfortable in France.
But my family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job anywhere else and I came across a vacancy with Air France here in Prague.
I have to admit that I did not know Prague at first.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my father even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I didn’t know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here for three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Mainly because of a completely different atmosphere.
Maybe it's because I don't speak Czech, so I can't catch some negative reactions or swearing, but I feel like people are freer here.
That I can do anything, dress in any way, and no one will judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you uncomfortably, for example, when you have special clothes and the like.
I started to feel really single in Prague.
Praguers don’t think they care about such things.
Where do you work now?
After working in Air France, I worked for a while for one travel site.
Then, with another friend, we set up a website where people offer and are looking for shared housing.
So far we operate only in Prague, but we would like to expand it to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends who are half Czech and two more friends of Czech.
I have to say that the next specificity of the Czechs is that they initially hold their distance more.
He won't let anyone in the body.
That's quite a difference from the place where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses on the cheek.
It's different here, but I understand it's a cultural thing, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned not to speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem for you?
On the contrary, I have it quite simple in Prague, because perhaps everyone here speaks English.
Even in curfews or in food.
I want to learn Czech, but I don't have that much time.
And by the fact that everyone can communicate at least a little bit in English, I do not need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone to help me.
Have you encountered any negative reactions?
Maybe because you're Muslim?
Basically, no.
Maybe it's also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My leader, the Czech woman, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense of: They are not French, but Africans.
That kind of touched me.
But that someone would have a problem with being a Muslim, that hasn't happened to me yet.
Even though a colleague once alerted me to some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He said not to go downtown, that they'd be swearing at me.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly related to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels can happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that anything can happen anywhere these days.
Until recently, I could not have imagined that something like this had happened in France.
This is not just for Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence at all.
For me, the people who kill are not Muslims.
The Qur'an says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists shield themselves with your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even if I shouldn't feel that way.
I try not to follow the reports of violence, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that is not my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for terrorists?
We met in Jiřího z Poděbrad Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians demonstrated against violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they do not agree with the violence.
I don't think they have to do that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't cause?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My collaborators are from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They are a bit more religiously based than me, so sometimes we have quite wild discussions about Islam, because we all perceive it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, they taught Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of women.
How do you see it?
I don't feel subordinate in any way.
Rather the opposite.
I'm a woman, I have strength.
It also has to do with the fact that you do not wear a headgear.
For example, a hijabi?
And it mainly reflects the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a really principled Muslim.
They pray five times a day, but the scarf just doesn't wear.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It depends on everyone as they interpret it.
When you read the Koran, you should make up your own mind about these things.
So when I read a passage in the Koran that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself, “I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I come to Iran or Saudi Arabia, where the headscarves require, I take it.
Do you plan to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
I didn't feel so good anywhere else.
I thought about Poland for a while, but I feel great in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is an ideal city for this.
