Behind the idea to use already planned trips for transporting shipments are TV director Matěj Liška and manager of the Prague music club Marek Greger.
With the idea, they breathed life into three applications with different geographical reach.
We launched the national Převez app in May.
At the moment, there are thousands of cities recorded in it and we will expand the network.
In the Czech Republic, we want to learn this first than we will focus more on abroad, says a forty-one-year-old manager in an interview for iDNES.cz.
How does the Transfer I App and who can benefit from it?
You download it and register for free.
Then you can enter the route and data on how much you can transport the package and how much you want for it.
Someone is asking for a transfer on that day.
When the route and time of delivery are convenient, it is paired and both come with a mutual notification.
At that moment, the chat opens, where the pair arranges the handover.
How many people would have to register by estimating so that each package always finds their courier?
I do not know the ideal state, I cannot estimate how many registered and how many trips are needed to make the coverage absolutely optimal and each supply is paired with demand.
It already works on the main roads and it is logically easier than on the road between villages.
The more people, the greater the potential for speed and accuracy.
People are also building their trust in the meantime and find that no one will run away with the package.
Have you had to deal with such a case yet?
How many users does the service have two months after launch?
At the moment, we have about 5 to 6 thousand people who create paths.
