Is a Qualification Agreement Necessary?
If I did not apply, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could go to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work without registering in special education after graduation?
My point is that in the field where I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a somewhat more distant hospital, but in about six months it could be freed up space in another, where I would then like to work.
So I don’t know how to deal with the situation about half a year, the question continues.
It Responds Mgr. Lenka Vlková.
No legislation provides for an obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - a hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institute regulated by the Labour Code and may be concluded between the employee and the employer in order to ensure the return on the costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee's qualifications.
In the field of health, there is a long-term pressure to not conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the labour mobility of healthcare professionals, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to the Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognizing professional competence and specialized competence for the exercise of the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, expressly, participation in specialized education is considered to be the deepening of qualifications (not for increasing it).
This means that the qualification agreement can only be concluded under the Labour Code if the costs amount to at least CZK 75 000.
No legal regulation nor does it impose an obligation to apply for specialization education.
The law only lays down the conditions for applications for inclusion in the field of specialized education.
However, according to the law, the doctor is entitled to exercise the profession of a doctor already thanks to the necessary university studies, albeil under the statutory conditions (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law foresees a situation where professional experience completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialized education of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
In theory, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the questioner’s situation.
However, due to the fact that I do not know the more detailed circumstances of this case, it is recommended to consult with the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (State of Science and Medical Professions), as the Ministry of Health provides a counselling and consulting service related to the inclusion in specialization education and its course.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
Doctors from Halab, Syria, are asking for U.S. intervention.
The United States has made no effort to end the siege (the rebellious part of the city by government troops) and did not use its influence to enforce the protection of civilians, AFP quoted from a letter addressed to the White House.
"We don't need tears, compassion, and even prayers; but we desperately need to create a no-fly zone over eastern Halab to stop the attacks, and we need an international action to ensure that Halab is not encirculated again," the doctors said.
Russian forces that support the military loyal to President Bashar al-Assada have announced that from today they will stop strikes in the Halab region every day for three hours to allow the humanitarian convoys to safely pass.
From 9:00 to 12:00 CELČ, all military activities, airstrikes and artillery fire are to be stopped.
U.N. humanitarian chief Stephen O'Brien welcomed this, but stressed the need for at least a two-day ceasefire.
According to AFP, 15 of the 35 doctors who work in the eastern part of Halab are controlled by rebels have appealed to Obama in the letter.
They write that during the five-year war they witnessed the violent, cruel deaths of countless patients, friends and colleagues.
The world watches and states how complex Syria is, but it does little to protect us.
Recent offers of evacuation of residents from the Syrian regime and Russia sound only slightly blurred threats, pointed out by pediatricians, surgeons and other doctors.
Doctors said in the past month there have been 42 attacks on medical facilities in Syria, 15 of them from hospitals in which they work.
We are most saddened that we have to decide who will live and who will die.
Young children come to the emergency room with such serious injuries that we have to choose among them those who are most likely to survive.
And sometimes we don't even have the necessary material to help them, doctors have described.
Two weeks ago, four newborns suffocated when the explosion interrupted the supply of oxygen to their incubators.
They were gasping for breath, and then their lives ended - before they could actually begin, they recalled.
The army loyal to President Bashar al-Assada, which is supported by Russian forces, has surrounded the rebel-controlled eastern part of Halab in recent weeks, with more than 200,000 people living inside.
The rebels, who are under constant strikes by the Russian and Syrian air force, managed to break the encirclement on Saturday after three weeks and launch a counteroffensive.
Both sides then added reinforcements in the city and its surroundings.
